As the industrial revolution advanced across
Europe and North America, differences in countries'

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:06.720
patent laws piqued an interest in creating
international standards for patents. The International

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:10.400
Convention for the Protection of Intellectual
Property, commonly known as the Paris Convention,

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:15.710
was signed in 1883. In Paris, France. Like
the Berne Convention, the Paris Convention

00:06:15.710 --> 00:06:19.920
lacks an adequate enforcement mechanism. If
a country violates the treaty, everybody's

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:25.160
back in the International Court of Justice.
But, just as with copyrights, nobody does this.

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:28.720
Because the Paris Convention didn't really
set minimum standards, countries had great

00:06:28.730 --> 00:06:32.290
freedom to tailor their patent laws to their
own needs and interests. Developing countries,

00:06:32.290 --> 00:06:36.080
for example, might exclude pharmaceutical
products from patentability because they feel

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.280
like health-related products and medicine
should be affordable for people to buy. Many

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:45.180
developed nations successfully sought to close
this gap during negotiations of our old frenemy,

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:48.830
the TRIPS Agreement. TRIPS incorporates parts
of the Paris Convention and sets forth a number

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:53.060
of minimum standards for patent protection.
TRIPS prevents World Trade Organization members

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:57.160
from denying patents to pharmaceuticals or
biotechnology products or processes.

00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:00.720
Unlike the Berne Convention, which does away
with copyright formalities, the Paris Convention

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:04.470
assumes that the inventor has to apply to
his or her particular government's patent

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:08.130
office or government. Countries that are party
to the convention can't give foreign inventors

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:12.420
a hard time. They get the same protections
that apply to domestic inventors. The Patent

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:16.310
Cooperation Treaty makes this easier. It helps
coordinate procedures for filing multiple

00:07:16.310 --> 00:07:19.760
patent applications for the same invention
in several countries around the world.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:20.680
Thanks, Thought Bubble.

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:25.080
So, the Paris Convention also governs trademarks.
In many ways, it treats trademarks like patents.

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:28.680
It requires countries to provide for national
treatment. Because trademark law is territorial

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:32.140
and you have to apply for protection in each
country where use is planned, there are two

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:35.920
special agreements that establish a common
international registration system. These are

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:41.160
the 1891 Madrid Agreement Concerning the International Registration of Marks and the 1989 Madrid

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:43.560
Protocol for Relating to the Madrid Agreement.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:47.870
Aside from all these European capitals and
their agreements and conventions and protocols,

00:07:47.870 --> 00:07:52.150
the TRIPS Agreement extends protection to
geographical indications. This means that

00:07:52.150 --> 00:07:56.440
the word "Champagne" can only be used for
sparkling wine produced in France's Champagne

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:02.000
region. It also extends to words like Bordeaux,
Chablis, Parma ham, Roquefort cheese, Florida

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.850
orange juice, Vermont white cheddar, all that
business.

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:08.800
These issues have been a point of contention
between the US and the EU. Europe has long

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.630
pushed for greater protection of geographical
indications. Every time you eat Greek yogurt

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:16.710
or Feta cheese, every time you smoke a Cuban
cigar, every time you stir up a cup of Swiss

00:08:16.710 --> 00:08:21.130
Miss hot chocolate, every time you're confounded
by a Chinese finger trap, you're seeing a

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:23.800
potential geographical indication violation.

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:27.980
At the end of the day, international intellectual
property is all about setting minimum standards

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:31.410
and national treatment. It's about countries
treating the nationals of other countries

00:08:31.410 --> 00:08:33.300
at least as well as they treat their own.

00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:37.840
This push for standardization has caused some
problems. There are now so many IP treaties

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:42.419
and agreements and protocols in place that
it makes intellectual property reform difficult.

00:08:42.419 --> 00:08:46.790
So, for example, changing the law to reduce
the copyright term in the United States isn't

00:08:46.790 --> 00:08:51.740
just a matter of changing the US law. It's a matter of changing all of these international agreements.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:55.760
Just as individual nations struggle to keep
pace with our increasingly globalized world,

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:59.760
so does the international intellectual
property system. Both national and international

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:03.990
systems are struggling to find the right balance
of exclusive rights and public access to knowledge

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:06.540
in a world where borders are traversed with
a click.

